<br>
&quot;Walnan says 'The arcane art of Summoning is derived from the power of the elements which surround us.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now one thing people might say is, &quot;well how come the plus 60 spells specificly say things like, Child of Ro, and Rathes son?&quot;. But of course, most of the spells have names after a god later on. You can simply think of the names as &quot;blueprints&quot; if you will. The Mage used say a Child of Ro as the blueprint for the fire elemental he summons at 63. <br>
<br>
Looking at the cast messages you get, it would appear the Mage at least uses the elemental power from the elemental planes directly, to throw a pet together.<br>
<br>
<br>
One flaw some might find in this would be &quot;why does Host of the Elements say they are called back to their home plane 30 seconds later?&quot; (I forget how long they stay up, but it's close to that)<br>
<br>
And this is where there is a problem. I suppose you could say a Mage summons the host of minions much the same way he summons a normal pet, but having so many running around takes more concentration then the Mage can endure for more then a few moments. And that returning to their home plane means the very elemental essence that they were derived from, gets called back to their respective plane.<br>
<br>
The thought of actually ripping an elemental from their own home plane always seemed off to me. In reality the devs probably have no idea what they would want their answer to be either. <br>
<br>
Ok, so I have an overactive mind. Maybe I go try and put it so use on something at least mildly productive now..........<br>
